SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890111-0217"
SELECTOR="K"
SUMMARIZER="K">  

A Boeing 737 jetliner on a flight from London to Belfast crashed
during an emergency landing at East Midlands Airport.  The pilot had
radioed that the right engine was on fire, then called again to say
that he had shut the engine down and was coming in for a landing.
Actually the left engine had burned and the pilot had shut down the
wrong engine.  The crash killed 49 people and injured 82.  The pilot,
seriously hurt, was being questioned by investigators.

Authorities are ordering checks on similar engines on other aircraft,
including the possibility of crossed wires on warning systems.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d59"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP880517-0226"
SELECTOR="K"
SUMMARIZER="K">  

A single engine Cessna P210 crashed into a ditch on the outskirts of
Albuquerque, New Mexico in squally weather, killing four adults and a
child.  The pilot had previously attempted a landing, but aborted the
try.  He was circling the field to try again when the crash occurred.
There was no fire, but the plane cartwheeled and all aboard were
killed.

An eye-witness, Walter Ramazinni, said that the plane had banked left
when a gust of wind caught him.  He banked to the right, then left,
and crashed. The National Transportation Safety Board will
investigate.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d59"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA081489-0225"
SELECTOR="K"
SUMMARIZER="K">  

All sixteen aboard a twin engine Otter were killed after it crashed
into a mountain in Ethiopia. The wreckage was found after a six day
search in poor weather.  U.S. Army search helicopters had to lower men
to the ground at the site, since there was no landing area on the
mountainside, where the grade is 60%.

The plane was carrying Representative Mickey Leland of Texas to an
Ethiopian refugee camp, one of several he was touring as Chairman of
the House Select Committee on Hunger, which he helped to
establish. Other government officials were aboard.  The cause of the
crash is under investigation.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d59"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ910304-0005"
SELECTOR="K"
SUMMARIZER="K">  

A United Airlines 737 jetliner has crashed in Colorado.  Twenty
passengers and a crew of five died as the plane nosedived to earth
while traveling from Denver to Colorado Springs.

This is the third crash of a United jet in three years.  In July, 1988
a United DC-10 crashed in Sioux City, Iowa with 110 fatalities, after
an engine broke apart in flight.  In February, 1989, the cargo door on
a United Boeing 747 opened in flight, ripping a hole in the fuselage.
Nine people were killed.

Wind shear is suspected in the latest crash.</SUM>

